member.name: M:DocumentFormat.OpenXml.Packaging.WordprocessingDocument.CreateFromTemplate(System.String)
member.summary: Creates an editable WordprocessingDocument from a template, opened on a MemoryStream with expandable capacity. The template will be attached to the WordprocessingDocument.
member.remarks: Attaching the template has been chosen as the default behavior because this is also what happens when a document is created from a template (other than Normal.dotm) using Microsoft Word.
member.param: The path and file name of the template.
member.returns: The new WordprocessingDocument based on and linked to the template.

member.name: M:DocumentFormat.OpenXml.Packaging.WordprocessingDocument.CreateFromTemplate(System.String,System.Boolean)
member.summary: Creates an editable WordprocessingDocument from a template, opened on a MemoryStream with expandable capacity.
member.remarks: This method is provided to offer the choice to not attach the template. When templates are attached in Microsoft Word, for example, the absolute path will be used in the relationship. These absolute paths are most often user-specific, however, so once documents are shared with other users, the relationship gets "broken" anyhow.
member.param: The path and file name of the template.
True, if the template should be attached to the document.
member.returns: The new WordprocessingDocument based on and linked to the template.

member.summary: Represents the xsd:integer value for attributes.
member.remarks:
Integer is derived from decimal by fixing the value of fractionDigits to be 0 and disallowing the trailing decimal point. The value space of integer is the infinite set {...,-2,-1,0,1,2,...}. The base type of integer is decimal.
Use Int64 as the internal type for now. TODO: Should decimal be used as the internal type?

member.name: T:DocumentFormat.OpenXml.Internal.SchemaValidation.DecimalValueRestriction
member.summary: Decimal (xsd:decimal) based value restriction.
member.remarks: decimal represents a subset of the real numbers, which can be represented by decimal numerals. The value space of decimal is the set of numbers that can be obtained by multiplying an integer by a non-positive power of ten, i.e., expressible as i 10^-n where i and n are integers and n >= 0. Precision is not reflected in this value space; the number 2.0 is not distinct from the number 2.00. The order-relation on decimal is the order relation on real numbers, restricted to this subset.

member.name: P:DocumentFormat.OpenXml.Internal.SchemaValidation.DecimalValueRestriction.XsdType
member.summary: Gets the XsdType - type defined in schema.

member.name: T:DocumentFormat.OpenXml.Internal.SchemaValidation.IntegerValueRestriction
member.summary: Integer (xsd:integer) based value restriction.
member.remarks:
integer is derived from decimal by fixing the value of fractionDigits to be 0 and disallowing the trailing decimal point. This results in the standard mathematical concept of the integer numbers. The value space of integer is the infinite set {...,-2,-1,0,1,2,...}. The base type of integer is decimal.
!******************** TODO: at current, the CodeGen generate int for xsd:integer

member.name: T:DocumentFormat.OpenXml.Internal.SchemaValidation.NonNegativeIntegerValueRestriction
member.summary: NonNegativeInteger (xsd:nonNegativeInteger, ) based value restriction.
member.remarks:
nonNegativeInteger is derived from integer by setting the value of minInclusive to be 0. This results in the standard mathematical concept of the non-negative integers. The value space of nonNegativeInteger is the infinite set {0,1,2,...}. The base type of nonNegativeInteger is integer.
!******************** TODO: at current, the CodeGen generate int for xsd:integer

member.name: T:DocumentFormat.OpenXml.Internal.SchemaValidation.PositiveIntegerValueRestriction
member.summary: PositiveInteger (xsd:positiveInteger, ) based value restriction.
member.remarks:
positiveInteger is derived from nonNegativeInteger by setting the value of minInclusive to be 1. This results in the standard mathematical concept of the positive integer numbers. The value space of positiveInteger is the infinite set {1,2,...}. The base type of positiveInteger is nonNegativeInteger.

member.summary: Token (xsd:token) based simple type constraint.
member.remarks:
token represents tokenized strings. The value space of token is the set of strings that do not contain the carriage return (#xD), line feed (#xA) nor tab (#x9) characters, that have no leading or trailing spaces (#x20) and that have no internal sequences of two or more spaces. The lexical space of token is the set of strings that do not contain the carriage return (#xD), line feed (#xA) nor tab (#x9) characters, that have no leading or trailing spaces (#x20) and that have no internal sequences of two or more spaces. The base type of token is normalizedString
In Ecma376, most token are enumerations.
